of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:27.260
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.340
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:41.419
Can't wait to see you there. I am so excited to welcome our featured leader

00:00:41.419 --> 00:00:47.020
for today, Ross Farrugia, Data and Insights Engineering Product Family Lead at Roche

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:53.820
slash Genentech. And I will let him explain what that slash Genentech means. Ross, would

00:00:53.820 --> 00:01:00.020
you like to unmute and introduce yourself? Tell us a little bit about what you do and

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:05.099
also what you like to do for fun. Sure. Hi, Libby. Thanks for having me along.

00:01:05.099 --> 00:01:11.260
So yeah, the slash Genentech is our kind of U.S. company, but we merged with Roche many

00:01:11.260 --> 00:01:15.580
years back now. So most of the folks in U.S. will have known Genentech, but you might not

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:19.300
have heard of Roche so much because it's a Swiss company. In the rest of the world, and

00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:24.739
especially in Europe, Roche is a lot bigger name. So yeah, it's Roche slash Genentech.

00:01:24.739 --> 00:01:30.139
So my role involves supporting kind of overseeing a lot of data science tooling in the clinical

00:01:30.139 --> 00:01:35.339
reporting space. So all of the tooling that we use for analysis about clinical trials.

00:01:35.339 --> 00:01:41.940
So I sponsor packages in the open source space, such as Admiral, or maybe people have heard

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:48.699
of Teal for helping to create shiny visualizations. And in my spare time, apart from chasing around

00:01:48.699 --> 00:01:56.180
my young children, I like to play football or soccer as the U.S. folks would call it.

00:01:56.180 --> 00:02:02.339
Yeah, that's my main passion. Awesome. And I feel like I don't know if I heard you say

00:02:02.339 --> 00:02:08.539
this in your intro, but if you didn't mention it, you're one of the co-founders of Pharmiverse.

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:13.699
Yeah, absolutely. So if anybody hasn't heard of Pharmiverse, this is essentially an open

00:02:13.699 --> 00:02:18.979
source effort for the pharmaceutical industry to bring companies together who, in the past,

00:02:18.979 --> 00:02:24.179
we were all doing very similar things in this post-competitive space. So once the drugs

00:02:24.179 --> 00:02:28.339
have been identified, essentially you have to run the clinical trials, and that unites

00:02:28.339 --> 00:02:32.020
the clinical trials, build the submission packages that are going to go to the health

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:37.179
authorities. We're lucky that we have very harmonized industry level standards from an

00:02:37.179 --> 00:02:42.979
organization called CDISC. But yeah, we were all still working in silos, doing very similar

00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:48.059
activity, but each company repeating the same work. So Pharmiverse was an effort built

00:02:48.059 --> 00:02:54.380
initially around R, but we're also open to Python and other open source languages. And

00:02:54.380 --> 00:03:02.300
we've grown to have eight council companies involved. We have 400 co-contributors. And

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:08.339
in our community, we have almost 2,000 people and many more using our packages. So essentially,

00:03:08.419 --> 00:03:14.500
bringing companies together to, instead of repeating the same work independently, we now

00:03:15.139 --> 00:03:20.660
co-develop and share the build effort, share the maintenance effort, share the testing effort,

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:26.419
to build code, which is ultimately going to help to bring all drugs to patients a lot quicker in

00:03:26.419 --> 00:03:31.699
the future. And it's not just us that can use the solutions. Also, the health authorities are open

00:03:31.699 --> 00:03:37.380
to use them. So it even helps to improve and accelerate the review and approval process.

00:03:38.339 --> 00:03:45.139
This is a little bit of an answer to Mike's question in Slido. So Mike, if you wanted to

00:03:45.139 --> 00:03:49.380
unmute and ask a little bit about this, because your question sort of expands a little bit on

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:57.940
that. Yeah. I mean, hi, Ross. One question I had was like, people might be familiar with a CRAN

00:03:57.940 --> 00:04:04.660
task view, where basically you're saying, here's a set of packages that are associated with a

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:11.860
public or a specific data area. So how is Pharmaverse kind of different from a task view?

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:17.299
Yeah, that's a great question. I can actually, in the early days, from a lot of our traditionalists

00:04:17.299 --> 00:04:22.420
were saying, you just do a CRAN task view. That'll be enough. And yeah, it's a great question.

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:27.059
What we realized, though, is in the early stage of our adoption across our industry,

00:04:27.059 --> 00:04:31.700
we needed a little bit more. We needed to build a community around this. And actually, what we

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:37.140
wanted, instead of having just packages where individuals from solo companies were kind of

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:42.899
putting something out there, as well as I do in our industry, takes a little bit more for you to

00:04:42.899 --> 00:04:49.140
adopt and trust. So say Pfizer put out a package, and my company, Roche, we would look at it and

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:54.739
think, hey, do we really want to trust that? Do we really want to embed that in our workflows that

00:04:54.739 --> 00:04:59.700
ultimately are going to go towards submissions? But what about if we can come in and work with

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:06.739
Pfizer and we can share the effort, we can become co-licensed holders and ultimately share that IP,

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:11.380
it's a lot more likely then that you're going to take ownership and you're actually going to

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:15.299
believe and trust that. And then it gets to the point where you have things like Admiral now,

00:05:15.299 --> 00:05:20.339
where we've got 10 co-development companies behind the Admiral package. And then companies

00:05:20.339 --> 00:05:24.739
that aren't even co-developers, they're more likely to trust it because they're saying, hey,

00:05:24.739 --> 00:05:29.299
Roche and I are going to pull out now. Or even if they do, there's nine other companies there,

00:05:29.859 --> 00:05:36.100
that are maintaining this. So with something like open source, where I think the fear is always that

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:40.420
it's not going to be sustainable. And people are going to put something great out and it'll just be

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:46.260
one person behind it. And then six months later, they'll find something new to attract their time.

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:51.380
And then it disappears. With a community like Farmiverse, for a start, there is such a package,

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:56.339
but we already like it. We can find members of the community that can help to maintain it.

00:05:56.339 --> 00:06:01.220
But generally, we prefer that from the start, these things are built with numerous companies,

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:05.700
numerous individuals, and then you tend to get better solutions because they all bring their

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:10.660
individual experience and you build something that's not just fit for one, but potentially fit

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:20.820
for all. I hope that helps. Yeah. Can I ask a quick follow on, which is about curation. So do

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:27.459
you have some curators or some kind of people providing a little bit of overview? Yeah, we used

00:06:27.459 --> 00:06:33.859
to have working groups dedicated to different areas like data engineering and tables and graphs,

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:39.540
visualizations, and they would be the ones that would ultimately kind of decide what goes in

00:06:40.339 --> 00:06:44.019
the Farmiverse. And we started off trying to be quite opinionated, right? We didn't want

00:06:44.019 --> 00:06:48.820
lots of repeat packages doing the same thing, things like that. Actually, over time, what we

00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:54.019
decided was let's just democratize this across the whole community. We've got like almost 2,000

00:06:54.019 --> 00:06:58.820
people in this Slack. Let's let them all have a say. So now if anybody approaches us and they say,

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:03.059
hey, I wanted to add my package to Farmiverse, I'd like to come in and work with you,

00:07:03.059 --> 00:07:08.100
we open it up to the whole community to say, hey, do you like this? People comment, people say, oh,

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:13.859
it would be really nice to fill this gap or to enhance it this way. And then quite often,

00:07:13.859 --> 00:07:18.339
the maintainer of the package says, okay, come and be a contributor, come work with me. And yeah,

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:22.100
it's kind of nice because a lot of the time what we're doing now is just connecting people across

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:26.739
the industry that they were going to build that solution anyway. They didn't need us, but we can

00:07:26.739 --> 00:07:32.019
help them to supercharge it by bringing more people into that work. So it's become like it's

00:07:32.019 --> 00:07:37.779
lightly curated because as long as the community are happy, we're happy. We do have some inclusion

00:07:37.779 --> 00:07:43.779
criteria, of course, as well that we try to monitor. But yeah, generally, it's becoming

00:07:43.779 --> 00:07:47.619
to the point where it doesn't need us so much now. Like in the early days, we were the ones

00:07:47.619 --> 00:07:52.420
kind of banging the drum and make sure now it's become like a really natural kind of ecosystem

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:54.820
and a natural community, which is what we always hoped it would be.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:59.619
Thank you, Mike. Thanks for the great question. And thanks, Ross.

00:08:00.579 --> 00:08:04.260
We have a lot of questions that are about the farm river. So I'm wondering if we

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:13.540
could maybe combine a couple of them. I wanted to pull Lisa in because I know that this question

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:20.339
is sort of the same lines that we've been talking about right now. But I want to engage the whole

00:08:20.339 --> 00:08:24.820
sort of community here in this and talk about this in the chat because Lisa's question is a

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:33.859
little bit more expensive. Yeah. So I was just curious about, you know, I love this idea of

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:42.340
sort of taking competing companies but coming together to solve a common goal. And I'm just,

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:49.059
I would love to see this in other industries. So I'm just curious how the heck you did that.

00:08:49.859 --> 00:08:53.859
How do you convince people from competing companies to be like, yeah, we'll work on this

00:08:53.859 --> 00:08:59.619
together? I mean, I think I'm in the insurance industry right now and I just I sort of can't

00:08:59.619 --> 00:09:08.659
imagine how that would happen. But I assume we might have some really similar similarities.

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:15.140
Absolutely. So when we first we first spoke to our legal group, actually, and leadership's another

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:20.099
thing, company leadership. But we went to legal first because the first thing any company feels

00:09:20.099 --> 00:09:25.460
is, OK, what's your actual intellectual property? What's the stuff that, you know, is actually kind

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:31.700
of making you money around and you don't want to ever open that up to others. And we had a really

00:09:32.659 --> 00:09:39.380
great IP expert lawyer and he's very progressive thinking and very kind of an open source enthusiast.

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:46.340
And the way that he talked us through is that, OK, what value is there to open source and are you

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:52.500
by open sourcing, by bringing this together with other companies, are you ultimately going to get

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:58.580
more in return than what you invest? And we said, look, even if only if we do this and only one

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:04.739
company across the whole of our industry steps up and gives what we're given, then we cut our

00:10:05.859 --> 00:10:12.739
development and maintenance budget by 50 percent. So we just need one. So, OK, go find that one.

00:10:12.739 --> 00:10:18.659
Go find someone who can meet you halfway and let's give this a try. Let's make this,

00:10:18.659 --> 00:10:23.619
you know, make a pitch to our leadership to show that this has potential. We were very lucky in that

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:30.419
a colleague from GSK actually was on LinkedIn and was messaging similar and made a connection

00:10:30.419 --> 00:10:34.900
with somebody from my team. And it kind of snowballed from there. So we thought, OK,

00:10:34.900 --> 00:10:39.859
let's prove it. And the first piece that we really looked to do this in was a piece of work where we

00:10:39.859 --> 00:10:44.580
hadn't actually put pen to paper. We hadn't developed any code at that time. So it was

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:50.580
like a no risk strategy, right? Either it doesn't work and we're no worse off than when we started

00:10:50.659 --> 00:10:56.340
or through working together as one as one team, not like, OK, we'll do half the work over here.

00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:59.219
You do half the work over there and then we'll throw it over the fence. No,

00:10:59.219 --> 00:11:04.260
let's work openly together on public GitHub repo where we're all in it from the start,

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:09.780
open from the start. And we're just amazed. Firstly, that one company really stepped up

00:11:09.780 --> 00:11:14.979
and met us halfway. But then what we did is we reached out to leaders from across the industry

00:11:14.979 --> 00:11:19.940
and said, hey, we have this idea. Would you be willing to bring people forward?

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:24.659
And you don't have to develop right now, but just test out what we're building. Tell us,

00:11:24.659 --> 00:11:29.619
is this suitable for your needs? And we asked a number of companies. We were amazed that over

00:11:29.619 --> 00:11:36.340
10 companies stepped up and ended up with like 40 people testing. We had thousands of comments,

00:11:36.340 --> 00:11:41.460
loads of really useful things that helped us. And this was just one package and really helped

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:46.739
us to go into that design. And from there, we started to reach out and understand, well,

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:53.380
there's already a number of other companies doing similar stuff in other areas of the work that we

00:11:53.380 --> 00:12:00.820
do that we're also interested. So once you get one win, you show your leadership, they buy in,

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:05.380
they invest in you more, and they start to make more and more connections. And you find the

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:10.419
like-minded people. They're going to be whatever industry. They're going to be people that believe

00:12:10.419 --> 00:12:15.619
in the greater good and that a rising tide lifts all boats. Sometimes it's just finding them and

00:12:15.619 --> 00:12:21.059
having that time. So yeah, in a nutshell, that's like a little bit of the story of how we've gone.

00:12:21.059 --> 00:12:27.059
Does that help, Lisa? I think that she might not be able to unmute herself to say thank you,

00:12:27.059 --> 00:12:32.020
but I think that the answer is yes. And I see some nodding. So I think that that's great.

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:39.140
And this is definitely one of those things that is a problem across all industries, not a problem,

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:45.859
a challenge, right? Like how do we convince leadership of doing things that feels like

00:12:45.859 --> 00:12:51.380
giving away their IP or giving away power or giving away money when it's good for everybody?

00:12:52.580 --> 00:12:57.140
All right. Thank you, Lisa, for the wonderful question. Let's see what other questions we have

00:12:57.140 --> 00:13:02.739
here. And don't forget, everybody, you have a place to ask your questions on Slido and also

