upvote other questions. So go scroll through what other people are asking. I wanted to ask

00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:14.260
a little bit of an industry question. So Abigail, you have a question here that is a little bit more

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:19.859
industry focused. Would you like to ask that live? Oh, nope. You have an asterisk. I see that you

00:13:19.859 --> 00:13:25.299
added. Okay. I'm going to ask Abigail's question for her. Ross, what does career progression look

00:13:25.299 --> 00:13:32.179
like in your industry? Where can data scientists go for either leadership or IC roles? And I think

00:13:32.179 --> 00:13:35.780
this is a great question for you because I had the same question for you when I first talked to

00:13:35.780 --> 00:13:41.380
you. I was like, hey, were you in people leadership and now you're in like a more product or project

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:45.780
leadership role? How did that happen? So maybe we could combine those together.

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:52.340
Yeah, that's a great question. And we get this a lot in our industry because it's quite a technical

00:13:52.340 --> 00:13:57.219
career, you know, data scientists, but there's obviously a lot of kind of people leadership

00:13:57.219 --> 00:14:02.500
naturally needed. There's a lot of kind of project management tasks as well. So you can go numerous

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:06.900
routes. We all tend to start with the technical route. We want to learn the basics. We want to

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:13.219
really understand clinical trials and how to do analysis. And then as we progress, you tend to go

00:14:13.219 --> 00:14:18.020
one of two ways. Either you're progressing kind of leadership where you start to kind of

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:22.739
oversee teams of people, project manage deliveries, and then you may be going to

00:14:22.739 --> 00:14:28.179
people line management, very different, and or maybe go on the more technical route where you

00:14:28.179 --> 00:14:32.739
get more and more advanced technical skills and you take on larger projects. So instead of writing

00:14:32.739 --> 00:14:37.460
code per se, it's going to be used by a team of five people, you end up writing code that's going

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:43.059
to be used in a product for 1000 plus people. So it becomes a very different like level of skills

00:14:43.059 --> 00:14:49.460
that you have to have to build software versus building just like single use code. In my experience,

00:14:49.460 --> 00:14:55.539
or my personal journey, I went the more the leadership route. So I became a line manager

00:14:55.619 --> 00:15:00.820
in our statistical programming group. I was there for five years, I really, really enjoyed it. I loved

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:05.460
working with people, helping them to develop and helping them to make the best of themselves.

00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:10.419
But actually, it got to a point where we had a reorganization. And I got an opportunity to move

00:15:10.419 --> 00:15:16.179
sideways into more of a product leadership role and into a very technical group. And I've really

00:15:16.179 --> 00:15:21.539
enjoyed that as well, because I've stretched myself so much, I moved away a little bit from

00:15:21.539 --> 00:15:26.580
the technical side, getting back in now and seeing how in just those five years, all the tech

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:31.059
has advanced so much. And now we've got AI coming and all these great advancements

00:15:31.059 --> 00:15:36.419
that actually enabled me to get back to some of my earlier passion and get back involved there,

00:15:36.419 --> 00:15:43.460
whilst also still overseeing teams still leading product deliveries, but not having the people

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:49.940
management side of things. So yeah, there's lots of opportunities. And it depends on the way you

00:15:49.940 --> 00:15:54.419
want to go. I've got colleagues as well that have gone into totally different areas of the business

00:15:54.419 --> 00:15:59.780
using that kind of technical acumen to actually move into some of the more non-technical groups

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:06.900
that could benefit from knowledge of data scientists. So yeah, in large companies like

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:11.859
the one that I worked for, you generally find numerous pathways and there's no one size fits

00:16:11.859 --> 00:16:18.099
all. Well, this sort of leads into another question that we got that's anonymous. So Abigail,

00:16:18.099 --> 00:16:24.260
fantastic question, leads us into the anonymous question is, is it possible to break into the

00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:29.780
pharma world if you are a data scientist slash statistician with no experience there? I'm guessing

00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:36.099
that means no experience in pharma directly. And do you have any recommendations? So on the people

00:16:36.099 --> 00:16:40.099
side, like one of my proudest things of PharmaVest is that PharmaVest is there for the patients.

00:16:40.099 --> 00:16:45.619
Ultimately, we're doing this to help to speed up all drug submissions, not just the ones from

00:16:45.619 --> 00:16:51.380
Rostran and Teck. We're trying to help all companies to do submissions quicker and ultimately

00:16:51.380 --> 00:16:57.219
get treatments to patients all over the world a lot faster. Actually, on the people side though,

00:16:57.219 --> 00:17:01.940
I've been really like proud to see where folks that aren't in the pharma industry have heard

00:17:01.940 --> 00:17:05.699
about this, and especially kind of younger generations, like, you know, they really want

00:17:05.699 --> 00:17:11.540
to see open source thrive and pharma doesn't have the greatest reputation for many reasons.

00:17:11.540 --> 00:17:17.060
So it's really nice to see a younger generation being attracted to our industry, and then through

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:22.819
the open source collaborations, actually finding opportunities to jump in and learn the skills that

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:28.420
will then be able to go on to their resumes and help them to find employment. So it's very nice

00:17:28.420 --> 00:17:34.660
when you see somebody says, hey, I've been learning R, I've done it in academia, but I have no idea of

00:17:34.660 --> 00:17:39.219
the standards that we use, the kind of data standards that we use. I have no idea what you

00:17:39.219 --> 00:17:45.060
mean by clinical reporting, building analysis data sets called Adam, and, you know, very specific

00:17:45.060 --> 00:17:50.819
industry terms, but because they're passionate and they know enough about R, they can add some value,

00:17:50.819 --> 00:17:55.619
they get started with the good first issues, the, you know, the real beginner kind of things,

00:17:55.619 --> 00:18:01.459
and naturally the teams that they join are then willing to give back to them and to help say, hey,

00:18:01.459 --> 00:18:06.180
go read, there's open training where you can learn those skills here, and people actually

00:18:06.180 --> 00:18:11.459
helping them to upskill in those new areas. And yeah, through this, we've seen a number of people

00:18:11.459 --> 00:18:17.780
come to the industry where they wouldn't have considered pharmaceutical in the past. So yeah,

00:18:17.780 --> 00:18:23.219
it's been really nice to see that anybody through open source can get involved, and it's daunting

00:18:23.219 --> 00:18:28.180
at first, but I appreciate kind of just reaching out to people and kind of commenting on an issue

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:32.660
and GitHub saying, hey, I'd like to help. It can be daunting, but I can definitely say within the

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:37.699
pharmaverse, there's a lot of teams that are really looking for that, and they're very willing

00:18:37.699 --> 00:18:45.140
to bring new people in and to help them to grow. That's awesome. Do you see a sort of

00:18:45.939 --> 00:18:53.619
role inside of pharma organizations or teams that looks a lot like contributing to an open

